node.title: Petsc ASPIN solver
node.bodyText:
Hi there,
I came across a paper where an Additive Schwartz nonlinear preconditioner is used for phase-field fracture problems and it seems to work quite well. Apparently, this type of nonlinear preconditioner already exists in petsc. (https://petsc.org/release/docs/manualpages/SNES/SNESASPIN.html)
Has someone used this specific solver within moose? I am interested in trying it out, but I couldn't find an example with the syntax on how to define the blocks and how to modify the residual computation (to account for the nonlinear preconditioner).
I just observed that the author of the paper asked this question in early 2019 (https://groups.google.com/g/moose-users/c/w19VwqHtspU/m/cvzpirFABQAJ).
paper: https://www.researchgate.net/publication/359439046_Nonlinear_Field-split_Preconditioners_for_Solving_Monolithic_Phase-field_Models_of_Brittle_Fracture
@andrembcosta could you also post the link to that paper here? I'm also interested in using this solver.
https://www.researchgate.net/publication/359439046_Nonlinear_Field-split_Preconditioners_for_Solving_Monolithic_Phase-field_Models_of_Brittle_Fracture
I'll mention @fdkong here in case he wants to chime in. Otherwise hopefully I can weigh-in with a more informed answer in not too long

so I think that supporting ASPIN is definitely possible. Doing it in the way that is done in the paper you linked will probably be much easier after #22226 is complete as that will provide a very straightforward way to define subproblems based on variables. Note that I have created #22239 to keep track of progress made on supporting ASPIN

node.title: Thermal Hydraulics tutorial issues
node.bodyText:
Hello,
I am working through the thermal hydraulics module tutorial and the base input file will not compile for the conjugate heat transfer step located here: https://mooseframework.inl.gov/bison/modules/thermal_hydraulics/tutorials/single_phase_flow/step02.html
I am trying to run the base tutorial before modifying the file, but both my modified code and the original input file are throwing the same error shown in the picture below.

*** ERROR ***
Unable to find closest node!
I am not sure as to how the code is struggling to find the closest node since the only thing that has changed from step one to step 2 is adding the heat structure values which have the same geometry and elements as the core structure. Any tips would be helpful. Thanks.
UPDATE: I only get this error when using MPI. The code compiles and converges when only using a single processor.
@joshuahansel

Are you running with a distributed mesh? I'm unable to reproduce your error (I ran with MPI). However, if I additionally use a distributed mesh, I just get a segmentation fault...
I'm aware of one of our THM components, HeatTransferFromHeatStructure1Phase (which is indeed in this model), not being compatible with distributed meshes. I see from my run that it doesn't give an error message, so I'll at least fix that.
Just curious: are you planning on a model where you actually need to use MPI? Not that it's not possible, but usually THM models have a relatively small system size due to being primarily 1D, and thus it's not terribly beneficial to use more processors. In multi-app setups where we have a large number of flow channels, we usually restrict each THM sub-app to 1 processor. This is not to say that what you're trying to do is wrong, just that I'd like to be aware of any need to prioritize distributed mesh support in THM in the future.

node.title: PorousFlowUnsaturated dummy question
node.bodyText:
Hi all,
I have a simple aquitard-aquifer system with a well in the aquifer that de-saturates the medium. I have made two models one with actions and the other one using kernels. However, I am not getting the same level of saturation at the end of the simulation. Could you please give a hint of what I am doing wrong. Also why the saturation in PorousFlosUnsaturated action is an element variable and with kernels is at the nodes?
Code:
https://github.com/wangshengwa/PorousFlow-stuff
Thanks!
Wang

Hi @wangshengwa , i'm on holiday so I'm sorry that i can't explore your input files in detail.  I had a quick look and don't see anything obviously different between them.  As for the element-vs-node difference: the saturation is always computed by PorousFlow at the nodes (no matter whether you use an Action or Kernels), however, your PorousFlowPropertyAux (note, you correctly used a "constant monomial" saturation variable) will use just one of the nodal values for each element.  Hence, it really only provides an approximate view of the representation held internally by PorousFlow (remember that the finite element solution is only accurate up to the size of the finite element, so this approximation is never too bad).   Perhaps this answers your question (ie, perhaps you were comparing nodal values to elemental values)?

I understand now. Thanks a lot, this solves my question.
Wang

node.title: RenormalizeVector UserObject
node.bodyText:
I have what is probably a question that is easily answered. I am using the UO NormalizeVector that was kindly provided to renormalize a vector field that has to have unit norm. I execute on "timestep_end" (any other option like linear or nonlinear does not work iterations diverge right away)). When I dump data after simulations, there are typically some isolated nodes (using exodus output and paraview) on which the norm deviates somewhat from unity, sometimes up to 2. My question is: does RenormalizeVector renormalize on elements or on nodes? If it normalizes on elements I can understand that the value on nodes can deviate from unity, but if it normalizes on nodes the norm should be unity on all nodes at output (as the normalization is at timestep_end). Or am I misunderstanding something (not at all unlikely....)?
Cheers,
Olle
